    <name>
				<text>7.4.2.3 Which 2 x 2 matrix has an inverse?</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Which of the following matrices are invertible? Find the inverse where possible.</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li><p>\(A = {@A@}\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p></li>
<li><p>\(B = {@B@}\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</p></li>
<li><p>\(C = {@C@}\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]</p></li>
<li><p>\(D = {@D@}\) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]</p></li>
<li><p>\(E = {@E@}\) [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] [[feedback:prt5]]</p></li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>Recall that a \(2 \times 2\) has an inverse if and only if its determinant is nonzero.</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
    <li>The determinant of \(A = {@A@}\) is \(\lvert A \rvert = {@detWithSteps(A)@} = {@ev(detWithSteps(A),simp)@} \neq 0\). Therefore, \(A\) is <b>invertible</b>.</li>
    <li>The determinant of \(B = {@B@}\) is \(\lvert B \rvert = {@detWithSteps(B)@} = {@ev(detWithSteps(B),simp)@} \neq 0\). Therefore, \(B\) is <b>invertible</b>.</li>
    <li>The determinant of \(C = {@C@}\) is \(\lvert C \rvert = {@detWithSteps(C)@} = {@ev(detWithSteps(C),simp)@}\). Therefore, \(C\) is <b>not invertible</b>.</li>
    <li>The determinant of \(D = {@D@}\) is \(\lvert D \rvert = {@detWithSteps(D)@} = {@ev(detWithSteps(D),simp)@} \neq 0\). Therefore, \(D\) is <b>invertible</b>.</li>
    <li>The determinant of \(E = {@E@}\) is \(\lvert E \rvert = {@detWithSteps(E)@} = {@ev(detWithSteps(E),simp)@}\). Therefore, \(E\) is <b>not invertible</b>.</li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
